The '''A345''' is a secondary [[A roads in Great Britain|A road]] in [[Wiltshire]], England running from [[Salisbury]] to [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]] and the [[A4 road (Great Britain)|A4]]. The road is a main south-north link across [[Salisbury Plain]], which is renowned for its rich archaeology, and passes many ancient points of interest along its way.

==Route==

The road begins in [[Salisbury]] at the Castle roundabout and travels north out of the city, passing close to [[Old Sarum]] castle, taking a predominantly straight line to [[Boscombe Down]] and then [[Amesbury]] before meeting the [[A303 road|A303]] at Countess roundabout where it shares Countess Services with the major road. At this point it passes within {{convert|2|mi|km}} of the [[World Heritage Site]] at [[Stonehenge]]. Continuing north, the road passes near to [[Woodhenge]] and the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] [[Royal School of Artillery]] base at [[Larkhill]].  This part of the route can be hazardous as there are often [[tanks]] crossing and the road is susceptible to [[subsidence]]. The next significant places are [[Netheravon]], and then [[Upavon]] where the road briefly separates into a one-way system around the village, running concurrently with the [[A342 road|A342]] to [[Devizes]].  From here the A345 goes to [[Pewsey]], where the [[Pewsey White Horse]] is best viewed, and then continues on to [[Marlborough, Wiltshire|Marlborough]], ending at a roundabout leading to the High Street which is the A4 road.

== History ==

Originally the A345 extended north from Marlborough to a junction with the [[A419 road|A419]] at Commonhead, south east of [[Swindon]].  From there it went through Swindon to meet the A419 again at [[Blunsdon]].

When the [[M4 motorway]] was opened, the section from Marlborough to the motorway junction 15 became a northern extension of the [[A346 road|A346]].  From the motorway to Commonhead, the road became part of the A419, and the route through Swindon was renumbered [[A4259 road|A4259]] and [[A4311 road|A4311]].

Between Amesbury and Durrington a {{convert|0.8|mi|km}} section of the A345 was realigned further east away from the Woodhenge [[scheduled monument]] in 1968,<ref>{{cite web|title=A345 that was|url=http://www.sabre-roads.org.uk/wiki/index.php?title=File:Old_roads_007.jpg|publisher=The Society for All British and Irish Road Enthusiasts|accessdate=5 January 2013|author=Robbie George|date=6 November 2011}}</ref> crossing to a further west alignment and incorporating a new roundabout at its junction with the [[A3028 road|A3028]]. 

The southern terminus was originally further south along Castle Street at Salisbury market square, but with the opening of the Salisbury Inner Ring Road in 1969<ref>{{cite web|url=http://history.wiltshire.gov.uk/community/getcom.php?id=193|title=Wiltshire Community History - Salisbury|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Wiltshire Council|access-date=|accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref> the southern section was declassified.

