In [[Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth]], '''galils''' were administrative units of [[Jew]]ish internal autonomy. <ref name=scep>''Scepter of Judah: The Jewish Autonomy in the Eighteenth-Century Crown Poland'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=1fGQfpMdp84C&pg=PA6 pp. 6]</ref> They were governed by Jewish regional councils (''[[va'ad]] galil'').<ref name=yivo>[http://www.yivoencyclopedia.org/article.aspx/Councils "Councils"], ''The YIVO Encyclopedia of Jews in Eastern Europe''</ref>
While initially they matched the Polish structure of ''[[voivodship]]s'' and other administrative divisions in other parts of the Commonwealth, over time the discrepancies between the state internal borders and those of the Jewish autonomy grew quite pronounced.<ref name=yivo/>
