[[File:Gansu Museum 2007 236.jpg|thumb|250px|Buddha Triad of the [[Tang dynasty]] from Tiantishan at [[Gansu Provincial Museum]]]] The '''Tiantishan Caves''' ({{zh|s=天梯山石窟|p=Tiāntīshān shíkū}}) are a series of [[rock cut architecture|rock cut]] [[Buddhist art|Buddhist]] cave temples in the [[Liangzhou District]] of [[Wuwei, Gansu|Wuwei]], [[Gansu]], northwest [[China]]. Excavated from the eastern cliffs of the Huangyang River (黃羊河) in the [[Qilian Mountains]] from the time of the [[Northern Liang]], carving, decoration and subsequent modification of the caves continued through the [[Northern Wei]] and [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] to the [[Qing dynasty]].<ref name="Getty">{{cite book |url=http://www.getty.edu/conservation/publications_resources/pdf_publications/pdf/silkroad6_b.pdf |title=Conservation of Ancient Sites on the Silk Road: Proceedings of an International Conference on the Conservation of Grotto Sites |editor=Agnew, Neville |chapter=Pigment Analysis of Polychrome Statuary and Wall Paintings of the Tiantishan Grottoes |author1=Zhou Guoxin |author2=Zhang Jianquan |author3=Cheng Huaiwan |publisher=[[Getty Conservation Institute]] |year=1997 |isbn=978-0892364169 |pages=362 ff.}}</ref> The complex is identified with the Liangzhou Caves opened during the time of [[Juqu Mengxun]] "one hundred [[Li (unit)|li]] to the south of [[Wuwei, Gansu#History|Liangzhou]]", as recorded in the ''[[Spring and Autumn Annals of the Sixteen Kingdoms]]'' and ''[[Fayuan Zhulin]]''.<ref name="Getty"/><ref name="Wuwei">{{cite book |script-title=zh:武威天梯山石窟 |trans-title=The Grottoes in the Tianti Mountain, Wuwei |author1=Zhang Xuerong |author2=He Jingzhen |author3=Wu Yiru |publisher=Cultural Relics Publishing House |year=2000 |isbn=7501012202 |pages=8, 292–5}}</ref> The name Tiantishan consists of three [[Chinese characters]] ({{linktext|天}}{{linktext|梯}}{{linktext|山}}) that literally translate as "Ladder to Heaven Mountain".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://gansu.chinadaily.com.cn/2013-11/02/content_17076178.htm |title=Tiantishan Grottoes (Wuwei) |work=[[China Daily]] |date=2 November 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>
==Caves== The [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] monk [[Daoxuan]] in his ''Ji shenzhou sanbao gantong lu'' ascribes the opening of Tiantishan to the [[Xiongnu]] king of [[Northern Liang]] [[Juqu Mengxun]]'s devotion to "meritorious deeds" alongside his desire to avoid the [[Impermanence#Buddhism|impermanence]] of the city by fashioning caves from the mountains.<ref name="Religion">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q2nWdWbN3MQC&pg=PA584 |title=Early Chinese Religion: The Period of Division (220–589 AD) |editor1=John Lagerwey |editor2=Pengzhi Lü |publisher=[[Brill Publishers|BRILL]] |year=2010 |isbn=978-9004175853 |pages=584 ff.}}</ref> Contrary to the account in the ''[[Wei Shu]]'' of monks and Buddhist teachers relocating to the east after the conquest of the [[Northern Liang]] by the [[Northern Wei]] and subsequent persecution, structural, iconographic, and stylistic analysis shows that activity at the site continued.<ref name="Wuwei"/><ref name="Religion"/> A total of nineteen caves in three tiers have been identified:<ref name="Wuwei"/>
{| class="wikitable sortable" |- !width="15%" align="left" | Cave !width="20%" align="left" | Construction !width="50%" align="left" | Modifications !width="25%" align="left" | Type |- | Cave 1 || [[Northern Liang]] || [[Northern Wei]], [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] (beginning, early, mid, and late), [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]], [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] || central pillar |- | Cave 2 || beginning of the [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] || early [[Tang dynasty|Tang]], [[Western Xia]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || square |- | Cave 3 || beginning of the [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] || [[Western Xia]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || square |- | Cave 4 || [[Northern Liang]] || [[Northern Wei]], [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] (early and mid), [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]], [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] || central pillar |- | Cave 5 || uncertain || uncertain || |- | Cave 6 || uncertain || [[Tang dynasty|Tang]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]], [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] || square |- | Cave 7 || [[Northern Wei]] || [[Northern Zhou]], [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || square |- | Cave 8 || [[Northern Wei]] || [[Northern Zhou]], [[Sui dynasty|Sui]], [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] (early and mid), [[Song dynasty|Song]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || square |- | Cave 9 || [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] || [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || square |- | Cave 10 || uncertain || uncertain || |- | Cave 11 || uncertain || uncertain || |- | Cave 12 || uncertain || uncertain || |- | Cave 13 || [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] || [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]], [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] || |- | Cave 14 || [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] || [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || |- | Cave 15 || [[Northern Liang]] to [[Northern Wei]] || [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || |- | Cave 16 || [[Northern Wei]] || [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]] || |- | Cave 17 || [[Northern Liang]] to [[Northern Wei]] || [[Sui dynasty|Sui]], [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] (mid), [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]] || |- | Cave 18 || [[Northern Liang]] || [[Northern Wei]], [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] (late), [[Western Xia]], [[Yuan dynasty|Yuan]], [[Ming dynasty|Ming]], [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] || central pillar |- | Cave 19 || uncertain || uncertain || square |- |}
==Later history== Tiantishan disappeared from the historical record after the [[Tang dynasty]].<ref name="Wuwei"/> While decoration and modification of the caves continued into the [[Qing dynasty]], five suffered from collapse over the centuries, exacerbated by an earthquake in 1927.<ref name="Wuwei"/> Despite initial survey in the early 1950s demonstrating the importance of the site, in April 1959 the Gansu provincial government approved the construction of a reservoir that would flood two of the three tiers of caves when commissioned in May the following year.<ref name="Wuwei"/> In the interval, a research team from the [[Dunhuang Research Academy|Dunhuang Academy]] and [[Gansu Provincial Museum]] documented the site and excavated the collapsed caves, although all the written records and colour photographs and most of the black-and-white photographs have since been lost, along with most of the copies of the wall paintings.<ref name="Wuwei"/> Some {{convert|50|sqm}} of the paintings were [[Detachment of wall paintings|detached]], although the colours have since "faded after 40 years of natural weathering", and other than for the largest, most of the sculptures were taken down and removed to the Museum.<ref name="Wuwei"/> In 2001, in recognition of their [[Values (heritage)|significance]] as one of the earliest [[Buddhist]] grotto sites in the country, the Tiantishan Caves were designated a [[Major Historical and Cultural Site Protected at the National Level]] by [[State Administration of Cultural Heritage|SACH]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sach.gov.cn/col/col1644/index.html |script-title=zh:全国重点文物保护单位 |trans-title=Major National Historical and Cultural Sites |publisher=[[State Administration of Cultural Heritage]]| language=Chinese |accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>
