{{Infobox feature on celestial object |name = Tupo |image = PIA20309-Ceres-DwarfPlanet-Dawn-4thMapOrbit-LAMO-image19-20151224.jpg |caption = Dawn photo showing selected crater features, Sintana crater is on top |image_size = 300px |type = |location = [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] |coordinates= {{coord|32.35|S|88.38|E|globe:ceres_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} |coordinates_footnotes = <ref name="GPN">{{cite web |title=Planetary Names: Crater, craters: Sintana on Ceres |url=http://planetarynames.wr.usgs.gov/Feature/15418 |date=15 October 2015 |publisher=Gazeteer of Planetary Nomenclature|work=[[USGS]] |accessdate=31 August 2017}}</ref> |length = |width = |diameter = 37 km |depth = |area = |dimensions = |peak = |discoverer = |naming = |eponym = [[Mangarevan mythology|Mangarevan god]] }} '''Tupo''' <!--{{IPAc-en|}} -->is a large crater in the middle of the southern hemisphere of the dwarf planet [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]], located at 32.35° S, 88.38° E. It has a diameter of 37 km. The crater is named after an obscure [[Mangarevan mythology|Mangarevan god]] of disorder (perhaps the same as Tu or Tupa), involved in turmeric planting<ref name="GPN"/> It was officially named by the [[International Astronomical Union|IAU]] on July 3, 2015.<ref name="GPN"/>
Nearby prominent craters are Tafakula and the tiny Braciaca to the north, the gigantic [[Kerwan (crater)|Kerwan]] towards the east-center part of Ceres in Vendimia Planitia, Chaminuka further southeast and [[Darzamat (crater)|Darzamat]] to the southwest. Due west of Tupo is a hill feature known as Niman Rupes.
