{{Infobox mountain range <!-- *** Name section *** --> | name = Willapa Hills | native_name = | other_name = <!-- secondary names --> | etymology = <!-- *** Image *** --> | photo = | photo_size = | photo_alt = | photo_caption = <!-- *** Country etc. *** --> | country = United States | state = [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] | region = [[Western Washington]] | parent = [[Pacific Coast Ranges]] | border = Columbia River | border1 = Olympic Mountains | border2 = Pacific Ocean | border3 = Cascade Range <!-- *** Locations *** --> | highest = Boistfort Peak | elevation_m = 949 | coordinates = {{coord|46|29|17.3|N|123|12|55.1|W|type:mountain_scale:100000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | part_type = Hills | part = [[Black Hills (Washington)|Black Hills]] | part1 = [[Doty Hills]] <!-- *** Map section *** --> | map = Washington | map_size = 300 | map_caption = Location of the Willapa Hills }} The '''Willapa Hills''' is a [[Geology|geologic]], [[Physiography|physiographic]], and [[Geography|geographic]] region in southwest Washington. When described as a physiographical province, the Willapa Hills are bounded by the [[Pacific Ocean]] to the west, the [[Columbia River]] to the south, the [[Olympic Mountains]] to the north, and the [[Cascade Range]] to the east.<ref name=ares>{{cite book |last= Ares |first= Adrian |title= The Fall River long-term site productivity study in coastal Washington |year= 2007 |series= General Technical Report, Forest Service Pacific Northwest Research Station |publisher= DIANE Publishing |isbn= 978-1-4223-2472-1 |pages= 15}}</ref> Some definitions place the Puget Lowland physiographic province east of the Willapa Hills.<ref name=dnr>{{cite web |title= Geology of Washington - Willapa Hills |publisher= Washington State Department of Natural Resources |url= http://www.dnr.wa.gov/ResearchScience/Topics/GeologyofWashington/Pages/willapa.aspx |accessdate = 2009-05-17}}</ref> Included within the province are the [[Black Hills (Washington)|Black Hills]], the [[Doty Hills]], and a number of broad river valleys, some of which open up into broad [[Estuary|estuaries]] on the Pacific such as [[Grays Harbor]] and [[Willapa Bay]].<ref name=dnr/> Other definitions do not include the Black Hills.<ref name=peakbagger>{{cite web |title= Willapa Hills |publisher= Peakbagger.com |url= http://www.peakbagger.com/range.aspx?rid=12213 |accessdate= 2009-05-17 }}</ref> The [[USGS]] [[GNIS]] defines the Willapa Hills as bounded by the Columbia River to the south and the [[Chehalis River (Washington)|Chehalis River]] to the north, without giving specific east and west bounds.<ref name=gnis>{{cite gnis |id= 1513656 |name= Willapa Hills |accessdate= 2009-05-17}}</ref> The Willapa Hills are one of the [[Pacific Coast Ranges]], which continue north as the Olympic Mountains and south, across the Columbia River, as the [[Oregon Coast Range]].
The highest point is {{convert|3087|ft|m|adj=on}} [[Boistfort Peak]]. The Willapa Hills are the lowest uplands in the entire [[Pacific Coast Range]] system. Almost all of the land is privately held and has been repeatedly logged. Only a few [[long corners]] remain with virgin forest. [[Alders]] less than twenty years old are typically harvested for [[pulp mill]]s.
The Willapa Hills receive abundant rainfall and a number of rivers originate in the region, including the [[Chehalis River (Washington)|Chehalis River]], [[Willapa River]], [[North River (Washington)|North River]], [[Bone River]], [[Niawiakum River]], [[Palix River]], [[Bear River (Washington)|Bear River]], [[Naselle River]], [[Grays River (Washington)|Grays River]], and [[Elochoman River]], among others.
